Great question! We can eliminate the manual `register()` functions using the **`inventory` crate** pattern. This allows the macro to automatically collect all builtins at compile-time.

Here's how to make it fully automatic:

## 1. Add `inventory` to dependencies

```toml
# Cargo.toml
[dependencies]
inventory = "0.3"
```

## 2. Create a builtin registry struct

```rust
// src/builtins/mod.rs or src/builtin_registry.rs
use crate::env::Environment;
use crate::value::Value;
use std::rc::Rc;

pub struct BuiltinRegistration {
    pub name: &'static str,
    pub function: fn(&[Value]) -> Result<Value, EvalError>,
    pub help: crate::help::HelpEntry,
}

inventory::collect!(BuiltinRegistration);
```

## 3. Update the `#[builtin]` macro to auto-register

```rust
// lisp-macros/src/lib.rs
#[proc_macro_attribute]
pub fn builtin(attr: TokenStream, item: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    // ... existing parsing code ...

    let expanded = quote! {
        #func

        // Submit to inventory instead of generating register functions
        inventory::submit! {
            crate::builtins::BuiltinRegistration {
                name: #name_to_use,
                function: #fn_name,
                help: crate::help::HelpEntry {
                    name: #name_to_use.to_string(),
                    signature: #signature.to_string(),
                    description: #description.to_string(),
                    examples: vec![#(#examples.to_string()),*],
                    related: vec![#(#related_vec.to_string()),*],
                    category: #cat_to_use.to_string(),
                },
            }
        }
    };

    TokenStream::from(expanded)
}
```

